Company Financials
  • PE Ratio: Price-to-Earnings: A measure of valuation.
  • PB Ratio: Price-to-Book: Compares a firm's market to book value.
  • ROE: Return on Equity: Indicates profitability by showing how much profit a company generates with shareholder money.
  • EPS: Earnings Per Share: Indicates company profitability.
  • Debt to Equity: Debt to Equity Ratio: Assesses a company's financial leverage.
  • ROA: Return on Assets: Indicates how profitable a company is relative to its total assets.
  • Current Ratio: Measures a company's ability to pay short-term obligations.
  • Quick Ratio: Measures a company's ability to meet short-term obligations with its most liquid assets.
  • Dividend Yield: The dividend income as a percentage of the stock price. Higher yields can be attractive to investors.
  • Operating Margin: Measures the percentage of revenue that remains after paying for variable costs.
  • Gross Margin: Indicates the percentage of revenue exceeding the cost of goods sold.
  • Payout Ratio: Shows the proportion of earnings paid out as dividends. Lower values can indicate sustainability.
